05667nam a22007815i 9780812292589DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979910579  a97808122925897 a10.9783/97808122925892doi  a(DE-B1597)469614  a(OCoLC)946106064  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJK2261b.S425 2016 7aPOL0150002bisacsh04a324.273223  aMD 89202rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122569:1 aSelinger, Jeffrey S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmbracing Dissent :bPolitical Violence and Party Development in the United States /cJeffrey S. Selinger. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b2 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Governance: Politics, Policy, and Public Law00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Legitimate Party Opposition and the Early American State -- tChapter 2. Economic Collapse and the Constitutional Construction of Party Politics -- tChapter 3. Th e French Revolutionary Wars and the Ordeal of America’s First Party System -- tChapter 4. Th e Second Party System and the Politics of Displacing Conflict -- tChapter 5. Union, Emancipation, and Party Building as Military Strategy -- tChapter 6. Redrawing the Limits of Legitimate Party Opposition: Party Politics and Its Discontents at the Turn of the Twentieth Century -- tEpilogue. Party Legitimacy, Th en and Now -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile the American founders fully expected parties to form in a free society, they were far less certain that opposing parties would peacefully transfer power from one to another. Party formation presented a confounding problem for the new republic: party rivalries could not be prevented, but they might, nonetheless, catalyze civil disorder or fracture the union of the states. The status of political parties has come a long way in American society and politics, however, and today American democracy is inconceivable without them.How did party competition become a regular and "normal" feature of the American political landscape? Why did American political leaders, who viewed such rivalry as a harbinger of the new republic's destruction, come to terms with party opposition? Embracing Dissent tells this story of political transformation, making the case that the status of party gained ground as the notion that party competition might instigate class violence, secession, or civil war, receded. From the American founding and the appearance of the Jacksonian Democratic party, to Lincoln's management of party politics during the Civil War, Jeffrey S. Selinger presents a careful reconsideration of American political development.Embracing Dissent also provides historical perspective on today's polarized political condition. Too often, pundits exaggerate the significance of partisan differences and minimize the depth of political consensus that permeates American politics. Political observers casually use expressions like "party conflict," forgetting, as the famed political scientist Giovanni Sartori noted, that public consensus on fundamental legal and constitutional norms makes party competition "something less than conflict, as we endlessly if often too late rediscover whenever we are confronted with the reality of a people shooting at each other." Embracing Dissent reminds readers of the long history of Americans "shooting at each other" and describes the political events that disarmed them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical partieszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh  aPolitical Sc